1.4.1	&quot;Restoring your EFS Private Key If you lose your Encrypting File System (EFS) private key (for example, your computer installation is destroyed, or you have reformatted), a designated EFS recovery agent must restore the files.	St
1.4.2	The designated recovery agent uses his or her EFS recovery agent private key to decrypt the files so they can be recovered.	St
1.4.3	To Restore the Designated Recovery Agent's EFS Private Key on Another Windows 2000 or Windows XP Installation: 1.	St
1.4.4	Log on to your computer using the local Administrator account, or an account that is a designated EFS recovery agent.	St
1.4.5	2.	St
1.4.6	Browse to the path and file name of the .pfx file to which you exported the EFS recovery agent's private key, and then right-click the file.	St
1.4.7	3.	St
1.4.8	Click Install PFX to start the Certificate Import wizard.	St
1.4.9	4.	St
1.4.10	Click Next and confirm the file location and name.	St
1.4.11	5.	St
1.4.12	Click Next.	St
1.4.13	Type the password for the private key, and then click Next.	St
1.4.14	6.	St
